  <section class="consulting-flow" aria-label="Consulting copy">
    <section class="consulting-block consulting-block--lead" id="working-with-knots" data-label="What I do" aria-labelledby="field-of-knots-heading">
      <img class="consulting-block-image" src="/assets/consulting/knot-03.png" alt="A symmetrical knot with grain flowing in concentric arcs around it." loading="lazy">

      <div class="consulting-block-copy">
        <h2 class="consulting-block-eyebrow" id="field-of-knots-heading">A field of knots</h2>

        <p>If you unfocus your mind&rsquo;s eye, a board full of &ldquo;knots&rdquo; &ndash; usually seen as defects &ndash; starts to look like the night sky: a field of galaxies feeling the pull of each other&rsquo;s gravity.</p>

        <p>After enough time working across disciplines and trades, I&rsquo;ve ended up at a <a class="consulting-subtle-link" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lagrange_point">Lagrange point</a> between things &ndash; close enough to feel the gravity, far enough to see the context.</p>

        <p>Most of the &ldquo;tools&rdquo; I&rsquo;ve picked up are for handling <em>knots</em>: places where the grain runs in several directions at once, and the next cut isn&rsquo;t obvious. A few I made myself; the rest came from other fields.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="consulting-block" id="getting-started" data-label="Getting Started" aria-labelledby="getting-started-heading">
      <img class="consulting-block-image consulting-block-image--crop-upper" src="/assets/consulting/knot-04.png" alt="Weathered pine with two knots and vertical splits running through the grain." loading="lazy">

      <div class="consulting-block-copy">
        <h2 class="consulting-block-eyebrow" id="getting-started-heading">Getting Started</h2>

        <p>If you would like to work together, send me a short or long note about the knot you&rsquo;re working on. Email or DM is fine. I&rsquo;ll ask follow-up questions to figure out whether I can be useful before either of us puts time or money down. The more context you share, the better I can dig in beforehand, and the more useful our first call will be.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="consulting-block consulting-arrangement" id="what-to-expect" data-label="Working with me: What to expect" aria-labelledby="what-to-expect-heading">
      <img class="consulting-block-image consulting-block-image--crop-lower" src="/assets/consulting/knot-01.png" alt="A pine board with several knots, including a cracked one near the center." loading="lazy">

      <div class="consulting-block-copy">
        <h2 class="consulting-block-eyebrow" id="what-to-expect-heading">Working with me: What to expect</h2>

        <p>Most engagements start with a paid &ldquo;thought sparring&rdquo; conversation: <span class="consulting-price">$350 for a 60&ndash;90 minute call.</span> I send a few prep questions a day or two ahead. The purpose of the call is for me to better understand the grain of the problem and find the next cut, while giving you a sense of whether you&rsquo;re <a class="consulting-quiet-link" href="https://stephango.com/in-good-hands">in good hands</a>.</p>

        <p>I only book the call if I&rsquo;m confident I can deliver more than $350 in value to you. If I can&rsquo;t, I&rsquo;ll tell you, and where I can, point you to someone who fits better.</p>

        <p>If $350 is too much, write anyway. Depending on your situation, there&rsquo;s flexibility on rate for early-stage or public-interest work.</p>

        <p>Beyond the first call, scope and rate are discussed and agreed in writing.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="consulting-more-knots" id="more-on-knots-section" aria-labelledby="more-on-knots">
      <img class="consulting-block-image consulting-block-image--crop-right" src="/assets/consulting/knot-02.png" alt="A long pine board with knots and grain flowing around them." loading="lazy">

      <div class="consulting-block-copy">
        <h2 class="consulting-block-eyebrow" id="more-on-knots">How I think about knots</h2>

        <p>A knot begins as a branch.</p>

        <p>Each year, with the turn of the seasons, the tree lays down another ring of wood around its core, just beneath the bark. Slowly the trunk thickens around the living branch, cocooning it beneath each new layer of growth. Year after year, ring on ring, knot on knot.</p>

        <p>If we could watch the process sped up, the tree would look strangely animate. Bark splitting, microfissures opening new living quarters for insects that depend on these warm retreats for shelter. New wood slowly climbing over old wood. Meanwhile the buried branch keeps drinking, still carrying water up through the trunk to leaves out beyond the bark.</p>

        <p class="consulting-asterism" aria-hidden="true">* * *</p>

        <p>The tree keeps growing toward the sun, laying down new road each spring on its journey toward the sky (while the weather&rsquo;s good for construction). A lot happens inside and outside a tree as it tries to make the most of this seasonal bounty of light, moisture, and warmth. You know what trees say. Make leaves while the sun shines.</p>

        <p>But arriving at a knot on the road, the grain has to take the long way around &ndash; bending the way spacetime bends around a black hole.</p>

        <p>Around the knot, the fibers crowd together, cross paths, switch direction without warning. Sometimes the wood hardens around the knot, making your tools skate <span class="consulting-tooltip"><span class="consulting-subtle-link consulting-hover-note" data-note="no matter how sharp" tabindex="0" aria-label="uselessly &ndash; no matter how sharp">uselessly</span></span> across the surface. Sometimes the fibers tear loose all at once and leave a divot where a smooth cut was supposed to be. Wood that read clear a few inches ago suddenly makes your plane act like a shopping cart with one bad wheel.</p>

        <p>Worst case, the plane finds a knot the way a car finds a telephone pole.</p>

        <p>It&rsquo;s a bad feeling when you hit a knot.</p>

        <p>This is usually where people begin blaming their tools.</p>

        <p>You learn to read ahead a little, and this habit of reading carries over into the rest of my work.</p>

        <p class="consulting-asterism" aria-hidden="true">* * *</p>

        <p>Hard problems aren&rsquo;t hard because nobody is smart enough or working hard enough. The nature of a living system is to make knots. No knots, no branches. No branches, no shade. No shade, no tree to fall asleep against.</p>

        <p>The grain starts moving in several directions at once.</p>

        <p>I can help you read the grain, describe the knot, and find the next cut.</p>

        <p class="consulting-end-ornament" aria-hidden="true">&#10086;</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="consulting-more-knots" id="common-knots-section" aria-labelledby="common-knots">
      <div class="consulting-block-copy">
        <h2 class="consulting-block-eyebrow" id="common-knots">Common knots and useful tools</h2>

        <p>To know which tool to reach for, we have to examine the knot.</p>

        <h3 class="consulting-subhead" id="wicked-problems-subhead">The problem with wicked problems</h3>

        <p>&ldquo;Wicked problems&rdquo; is a frame for hard problems. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1080/14494035.2019.1617971">The term has been used too many ways to mean much</a>. Once I&rsquo;ve called something wicked, I know it&rsquo;s hard. I don&rsquo;t know what kind of hard, or what to do next.</p>

        <p>One tool that offers a finer-grained perspective is <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Volatility,_uncertainty,_complexity_and_ambiguity">VUCA</a>. VUCA problems are characterized by four things:</p>

        <ol class="consulting-vuca-list">
          <li><strong>Volatility</strong> &ndash; frequent change; unstable conditions.</li>
          <li><strong>Uncertainty</strong> &ndash; lack of predictability; prospect of surprise.</li>
          <li><strong>Complexity</strong> &ndash; many confounding forces; no clear cause and effect.</li>
          <li><strong>Ambiguity</strong> &ndash; unclear how variables interact; mixed meanings of conditions.</li>
        </ol>

        <p>Each can be diagnosed and addressed separately, unlike wicked problems, which treat difficulty as a single category.</p>

        <p>Most knotty problems have at least two of these going at once, and a lot of what I do is figuring out which tools fit the knot in front of us.</p>

